something else, maybe related to a different type of stone.","dimension":17,"group":6,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.037482,0.079851,0.095452,0.10762,0.10075,0.098527,0.097446,0.09376,0.087679,0.079896,0.067708,0.053827],"unified_progress":[0.03258,0.066686,0.08608,0.097914,0.10221,0.10325,0.10413,0.10146,0.095605,0.090763,0.0715,0.047821]},{"section":9,"text":"Then there's the cyanide-nitroprusside test, which came back positive.","dimension":10,"group":1,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.03515,0.069234,0.087683,0.097155,0.10327,0.10305,0.10173,0.09663,0.090804,0.084148,0.072054,0.059094],"unified_progress":[0.037845,0.071584,0.088518,0.099083,0.10406,0.10322,0.10197,0.097275,0.092883,0.084088,0.068899,0.050573]},{"section":10,"text":"I think that test is used to detect the presence of certain substances in the urine.","dimension":17,"group":6,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.039912,0.074586,0.089849,0.10128,0.10125,0.10046,0.098786,0.09499,0.089001,0.081666,0.070082,0.058139],"unified_progress":[0.038336,0.071938,0.089427,0.098888,0.10314,0.10314,0.10355,0.097445,0.091308,0.084661,0.06909,0.049077]},{"section":11,"text":"Specifically, I recall that it's used to identify the presence of cystine.","dimension":1,"group":7,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.039296,0.068754,0.084247,0.096393,0.10099,0.10209,0.10152,0.098083,0.092587,0.084275,0.072288,0.05948],"unified_progress":[0.040598,0.073556,0.089888,0.098418,0.10334,0.10217,0.10289,0.096085,0.090327,0.083396,0.069216,0.050112]},{"section":12,"text":"Cystine is an amino acid, and when it's present in high amounts, it can form stones called cystine stones.","dimension":1,"group":7,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.037439,0.06544,0.081355,0.094687,0.10294,0.1053,0.10573,0.10166,0.094864,0.082875,0.070334,0.057378],"unified_progress":[0.042919,0.077055,0.094207,0.10186,0.10692,0.10494,0.10544,0.093882,0.087223,0.076844,0.063417,0.045291]},{"section":13,"text":"The test works because cystine reacts with sodium nitroprusside in the presence of cyanide, producing a color change that indicates a positive result.","dimension":1,"group":7,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.043367,0.062745,0.078294,0.090387,0.099408,0.10256,0.10385,0.10079,0.096059,0.085451,0.074579,0.062512],"unified_progress":[0.041132,0.071747,0.089312,0.097403,0.10413,0.10405,0.10478,0.095025,0.090458,0.08098,0.068967,0.052012]},{"section":14,"text":"Putting this together: the patient had a kidney stone that passed, urinalysis showed hexagonal crystals, and the cyanide-nitroprusside test was positive.","dimension":1,"group":7,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.03607,0.064349,0.074651,0.082521,0.089962,0.092461,0.093057,0.092063,0.090648,0.090885,0.09324,0.10009],"unified_progress":[0.038695,0.067174,0.078673,0.085892,0.09061,0.09158,0.094547,0.090653,0.090343,0.086044,0.090672,0.095116]},{"section":15,"text":"Hexagonal crystals are characteristic of cystine stones, and the positive test confirms the presence of cystine.","dimension":1,"group":7,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.033452,0.055547,0.069999,0.081574,0.089956,0.093938,0.096205,0.096618,0.095724,0.094597,0.094643,0.097746],"unified_progress":[0.035281,0.06249,0.076911,0.085354,0.091216,0.093233,0.096541,0.093003,0.092922,0.089894,0.091026,0.09213]},{"section":16,"text":"So, the most likely diagnosis is cystinuria, which is a condition where there's an excess of cystine in the urine, leading to the formation of these stones.","dimension":1,"group":7,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.038583,0.05848,0.070328,0.080142,0.086786,0.090604,0.094717,0.096085,0.095284,0.095532,0.094806,0.098654],"unified_progress":[0.035586,0.059484,0.073307,0.082477,0.088181,0.092653,0.09451,0.094439,0.095002,0.092638,0.094532,0.097192]},{"section":17,"text":"I don't think it's calcium oxalate or uric acid stones because those don't typically present with hexagonal crystals, and the test result here is speci